President Biden has announced his intent to appoint several individuals as members of the United States Holocaust Memorial Council. The council was established by Congress in 1980 to lead the nation in commemorating the Holocaust and raise private funds for the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum. The appointees include Kevin Abel, a former congressional candidate and founder of a technology company; Rabbi Michael Beals, who has been with Congregation Beth Shalom since 2004; Ted Deutch, former CEO of American Jewish Committee and a former congressman; Kimberly Marteau Emerson, a lawyer and human rights advocate; Alexander Heckler, an attorney and philanthropist; Danielle Borrin Hertz, a strategic initiatives leader for JPMorgan Chase & Co.; Jonathan Lavine, co-managing partner of Bain Capital; Harry Evans Sloan, former chairman and CEO of MGM Studios; Alan Solomont, former U.S. ambassador to Spain; and Gary Phillip Zola, a historian and executive director of The Jacob Rader Marcus Center of the American Jewish Archives.